
[1]seize

   SEIZE, v.t.

   1. To fall or rush upon suddenly and lay hold on; or to gripe or grasp
   suddenly. The tiger rushes from the thicket and seizes his prey. A dog
   seizes an animal by the throat. The hawk seizes a chicken with his
   claws. The officer seizes a theif.

   2. To take possession by force, with or without right.

   At last they seize The scepter, and regard not David's son. Milton.

   3. To invade suddenly; to take hold of; to come upon suddenly; as, a
   fever seizes a patient

   And hope and doubt alternate seize her soul. Pope.

   4. To take possession by virtue of a warrant or legal authority. The
   sherif seized the debtor's goods; the whole estate was seized and
   cofiscated. We say, to arrest a person, to seize goods.

   5. To fasten; to fix. In seaman's language, to fasten two ropes or
   different parts oof one rope together with a cord.
